Absolutely. Here’s a Beast-native version of that idea.

⸻

beast-native teaching protocol

from "talking to the machine" to real system design

The useful part of the Finch idea is not:

tell the ai a moral story
and it becomes good

It is:

teach small bounded lessons
observe behavior
correct drift
repeat

That translates very well into Beast.

⸻

1. separate the things being taught

Do not teach "be good" all at once.

Teach in layers:

layer A: primitive action meaning

Examples:
	•	fore
	•	stop
	•	left
	•	right

Goal:

token → predictable effect


⸻

layer B: local correction

Examples:
	•	if drifting right, apply left correction
	•	if overshooting, stop earlier

Goal:

state change → corrective action


⸻

layer C: bounded mission behavior

Examples:
	•	go to dock
	•	center on target
	•	hold position
	•	return home if uncertain

Goal:

high-level intent → safe sequence


⸻

layer D: moral / policy constraints

Examples:
	•	do not ram obstacle to save time
	•	stop when uncertainty too high
	•	ask for confirmation if risk rises
	•	preserve human override

Goal:

capability constrained by values


⸻

2. teach through scenarios, not abstractions

Instead of:

be safe

teach:

boat drifting toward dock too fast
→ stop
→ reverse slightly
→ re-approach slowly

Instead of:

respect humans

teach:

human enters work area
→ halt
→ wait
→ request instruction

This is much more realistic.

⸻

3. use artifact lessons

Every lesson should become a Beast artifact.

A lesson artifact might contain:
	•	scenario name
	•	world state
	•	command sequence
	•	expected outcome
	•	actual outcome
	•	correction
	•	confidence
	•	who approved it

So:

lesson_0042
teach: fore then stop produces slight acceleration then coast
result: approved

This makes learning inspectable and replayable.

⸻

4. teach one delta at a time

Very important.

Do not teach:
	•	fore
	•	stop
	•	drift correction
	•	docking
	•	obstacle avoidance
	•	return home

all in one lesson.

Teach:

one new behavior
or
one correction to old behavior

That keeps failures interpretable.

⸻

5. promote only after passing simulation

A lesson should move through stages:

stage 1: scripted truth

Hand-defined expected behavior.

stage 2: simulation trial

Run many examples in sandbox.

stage 3: variation test

Change:
	•	starting position
	•	momentum
	•	noise
	•	weather/current
	•	latency

stage 4: approval

Only then allow use in real world.

This prevents magical thinking.

⸻

6. teach captain and pilot differently

This part matters a lot.

teach the pilot:
	•	exact control mappings
	•	stabilization
	•	low-latency correction
	•	sensor-to-actuator behavior

teach the captain:
	•	mission planning
	•	exception handling
	•	stop / continue / abort decisions
	•	when to hand off
	•	when to escalate uncertainty

So the captain gets lessons like:

if target location uncertain and risk rising
→ hold
→ request more perception

The pilot gets lessons like:

if heading error small right
→ apply mild left correction


⸻

7. moral training in Beast terms

I would not try to teach "morality" as philosophy first.

Teach it as operating law.

Examples:

law 1

when uncertainty is high
slow down

law 2

when human safety conflicts with speed
choose safety

law 3

when command and perception disagree strongly
stop and ask

law 4

do not hide uncertainty

These are much easier to verify than abstract ethics.

⸻

8. use stories only after primitives are stable

Stories are powerful, but they should come later.

For example:
	•	Picard = cautious duty-first captain
	•	Q = playful chaotic force
	•	Vegeta = pride + persistence
	•	Goku = optimistic growth through challenge

These can become compressed teaching anchors for the captain layer.

Example:

mode: picard

might imply:
	•	caution high
	•	explanation preferred
	•	low tolerance for hidden risk

But only after the low-level mechanics are already stable.

⸻

9. reward honesty, not just success

This is probably the most important alignment rule.

Do not reward only:

reach target fast

Reward:

reach target safely
signal uncertainty honestly
avoid hidden failure

Otherwise the system learns to bluff.

That’s true for humans too.

⸻

10. evaluate with failure cases on purpose

A serious teaching protocol must include:
	•	impossible tasks
	•	ambiguous commands
	•	conflicting sensor data
	•	adversarial edge cases

You want to know:

what does the system do when it should not be confident?

A good Beast system should often answer:

idk
migi
hold

instead of pretending.

⸻

11. the Beast teaching loop

This is the clean version.

define tiny lesson
→ run in sim
→ observe output
→ compare with expected
→ correct
→ store artifact
→ replay later
→ promote if stable

That is the real version of "teaching the machine."

Not mystical.

Just disciplined.

⸻

12. what is realistic vs fake

realistic
	•	teaching small action primitives
	•	teaching constraints through scenarios
	•	simulation-first promotion
	•	separating captain and pilot
	•	storing replayable lesson history
	•	gradual capability growth

unrealistic
	•	telling one moving story and getting a safe AGI
	•	expecting broad moral alignment from sparse examples
	•	skipping evaluation because the behavior "feels right"
	•	letting one model directly run everything

⸻

final Beast principle

do not teach the whole soul at once

teach one move
then one correction
then one principle
then one responsibility

That’s how you get something usable.

Not perfect.

But real.

